  "is_vocab": false,
  "stimulus_html": "<p>One frequently used method for preparing methyl esters is by reaction of carboxylic acids with diazomethane, CH<sub>2</sub>N<sub>2</sub>.</p>\n<img class=\"scaled-down\" src=\"https://exercises.openstax.org/rails/active_storage/blobs/proxy/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaHBBazhYIiwiZXhwIjpudWxsLCJwdXIiOiJibG9iX2lkIn19--f19a7b2325696e7434782f4e8948899e05ee6a6c/OChem_21_EC_056.jpg\" alt=\"The reaction of benzoic acid and diazomethane gives methyl benzoate and molecular nitrogen.\">\n<p>The reaction occurs in two steps: (<b><span class=\"magenta-text\">1</span></b>) protonation of diazomethane by the carboxylic acid to yield methyldiazonium ion, CH<sub>3</sub>N<sub>2</sub><sup>+</sup>, plus a carboxylate ion; and (<b><span class=\"magenta-text\">2</span></b>) reaction of the carboxylate ion with CH<sub>3</sub>N<sub>2</sub><sup>+</sup>.</p>",
